1
00:01:42,100 --> 00:01:43,897
Don't mourn
for Joe Strombel.

2
00:01:45,170 --> 00:01:46,796
Joe Strombel led a full life.

3
00:01:48,640 --> 00:01:51,164
A newspaperman
in the best tradition.

4
00:01:51,977 --> 00:01:53,944
A great credit
to the fourth estate.

5
00:01:55,146 --> 00:01:58,081
It didn't matter
if the bombs in the
war zone were falling.

6
00:01:58,484 --> 00:02:01,647
It didn't matter
how high up
the political scandal went,

7
00:02:02,387 --> 00:02:04,617
or how many
big corporations

8
00:02:04,722 --> 00:02:07,213
or small-time racketeers
leaned on him.

9
00:02:08,393 --> 00:02:11,384
Whatever the risk,
if there was a story there,

10
00:02:11,864 --> 00:02:15,128
Joe went after it.
And he usually got it.

11
00:02:16,335 --> 00:02:18,427
Well, I was with him
when the story broke
about Prince Charles,

12
00:02:18,503 --> 00:02:21,301
and that made him
persona non grata
with the Royal Family.

13
00:02:21,372 --> 00:02:24,240
Except with Diana.
They always remained
good friends.

14
00:02:24,308 --> 00:02:25,936
(ALL AGREEING)
He did love a woman.

15
00:02:26,645 --> 00:02:28,509
Hey, did you know he started
as a police reporter?

16
00:02:28,579 --> 00:02:30,342
Did he?
Yeah, he was
a bloody good one.

17
00:02:30,414 --> 00:02:32,348
One of the best.
Maybe the best.

18
00:02:32,417 --> 00:02:34,850
I got trapped with Joe once
in Afghanistan.

19
00:02:34,920 --> 00:02:35,908
Yeah?

20
00:02:36,087 --> 00:02:38,180
And we were going
to be shot any moment
by the Taliban, until,

21
00:02:39,024 --> 00:02:40,685
typically, Joe found
someone to bribe

22
00:02:40,825 --> 00:02:42,453
(ALL LAUGHING)
So we could escape.

23
00:02:42,527 --> 00:02:45,587
MAN 1: Not with his own money,
though.
No, no, he got it on expenses.

24
00:02:45,663 --> 00:02:47,028
MAN 2: Plus 10%.
MAN 3: Ten percent.

25
00:02:47,299 --> 00:02:50,268
But it did
involve us getting out
wearing burkas.

26
00:02:51,002 --> 00:02:53,198
And, well, we lived
to write another day.

27
00:02:53,271 --> 00:02:55,001
Everyone loved him.
Yeah.

28
00:02:55,106 --> 00:02:56,768
MAN 1: Not always at
British intelligence.

29
00:02:56,841 --> 00:02:59,037
No, but he got
the information
before anyone else.

30
00:02:59,144 --> 00:03:01,169
Yeah, he did. That's right.
Not Richard Nixon, though.

31
00:03:02,046 --> 00:03:05,483
Well, wherever you are now,
Joe, it won't be the same
without you, mate.

32
00:03:06,384 --> 00:03:07,852
ALL: To Joe.
Joe Strombel.

33
00:03:26,103 --> 00:03:27,935
(SHIP CREAKING)

34
00:03:28,774 --> 00:03:29,900
(CLEARS THROAT)

35
00:03:29,974 --> 00:03:31,306
Where are we headed?

36
00:03:35,614 --> 00:03:38,582
Does this
mean anything to you?

37
00:03:45,924 --> 00:03:46,913
(SIGHS)

38
00:03:49,661 --> 00:03:51,686
He doesn't give answers.
Tried it.

39
00:03:53,198 --> 00:03:55,723
Joe Strombel.
Coronary thrombosis.

40
00:03:56,335 --> 00:03:57,699
Jane Cook.

41
00:03:58,236 --> 00:04:00,568
So, what do you do?
Reporter.

42
00:04:00,639 --> 00:04:02,163
Hmm.
You?

43
00:04:02,741 --> 00:04:07,336
I'm... Well, I was
personal secretary
to Peter Lyman.

44
00:04:07,778 --> 00:04:10,509
Lord Lyman's son.
Yes, impressive young man.

45
00:04:10,915 --> 00:04:12,781
You knew him?
No, only by reputation.

46
00:04:13,185 --> 00:04:14,550
But I like what I know.

47
00:04:15,387 --> 00:04:17,581
I think he's got
a real future in politics.

48
00:04:19,257 --> 00:04:20,350
How did you die?

49
00:04:21,560 --> 00:04:22,992
I think I was poisoned.

50
00:04:24,096 --> 00:04:25,084
You think?

51
00:04:25,930 --> 00:04:26,988
Why?

52
00:04:27,598 --> 00:04:28,930
I believe I was poisoned

53
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:31,834
because I was
on the verge of confirming
a terrible suspicion.

54
00:04:33,071 --> 00:04:34,867
Yes?
What suspicion is that?

55
00:04:36,507 --> 00:04:38,771
That Peter Lyman
is the serial killer

56
00:04:39,043 --> 00:04:41,672
known to the police
as the Tarot Card Killer.

57
00:04:42,781 --> 00:04:43,906
(CHUCKLES) What?

58
00:04:44,516 --> 00:04:46,177
I assume
you're aware of that case?

59
00:04:46,350 --> 00:04:49,718
Yeah, I wrote an article
two years ago, when the
Tarot killings first started.

60
00:04:49,788 --> 00:04:52,255
But Peter Lyman? My God.

61
00:04:53,024 --> 00:04:54,218
What on earth
made you suspect

62
00:04:54,293 --> 00:04:56,783
this rich, young handsome,
above-reproach citizen?

63
00:04:57,428 --> 00:05:00,091
You remember the last murder?
The police found a clue.

64
00:05:00,432 --> 00:05:03,492
Yes, a cufflink.
I read about it in the paper.
Unusual antique, wasn't it?

65
00:05:03,769 --> 00:05:06,202
Yep.
Very rare Art Deco.

66
00:05:06,771 --> 00:05:08,966
Peter had the exact pair.

67
00:05:10,175 --> 00:05:11,903
So could have
the Tarot Killer.

68
00:05:11,976 --> 00:05:13,569
The world is full
of coincidences.

69
00:05:13,644 --> 00:05:16,910
Yeah, except I noticed
that Peter only had one left.

70
00:05:17,415 --> 00:05:18,882
He'd lost the other.

71
00:05:20,285 --> 00:05:21,512
Still,

72
00:05:21,887 --> 00:05:23,615
although
it's a tantalizing thought.

73
00:05:23,689 --> 00:05:26,122
Did you inform the police,
or was that too sticky?

74
00:05:26,290 --> 00:05:28,418
I didn't know what to do,
so I phoned my lawyer

75
00:05:28,492 --> 00:05:30,723
and I asked his advice
on whether to
report it or not.

76
00:05:31,129 --> 00:05:34,394
And I thought
I heard this click
on the phone,

77
00:05:34,733 --> 00:05:36,598
you know, like someone
had been listening.

78
00:05:37,069 --> 00:05:38,798
Later that day, after tea,

79
00:05:39,870 --> 00:05:41,771
I died suddenly.

80
00:05:46,444 --> 00:05:48,207
That is suspicious.

81
00:05:51,283 --> 00:05:53,911
My God, Peter Lyman.

82
00:05:54,052 --> 00:05:56,451
Hard to believe,
but if he did turn out
to be the Tarot Killer,

83
00:05:57,254 --> 00:05:58,415
what a story.

84
00:05:58,490 --> 00:06:01,117
I knew you'd appreciate it
when you said
you were a reporter.

85
00:06:01,192 --> 00:06:04,093
This would be
a dynamite scoop.
And I got it first.

86
00:06:04,161 --> 00:06:07,221
Yeah. Unfortunately,
where you're headed
there is no first.

87
00:06:07,331 --> 00:06:08,992
There's only last.

88
00:06:19,845 --> 00:06:21,369
REPORTER 1: Mr. Tinsley!
Loved your last picture.

89
00:06:21,446 --> 00:06:22,776
You really have a way
with actors.

90
00:06:22,848 --> 00:06:24,213
Think you could maybe...
Please wait!

91
00:06:25,983 --> 00:06:27,747
Mr. Tinsley?
Yeah.

92
00:06:28,487 --> 00:06:30,954
Sondra Pransky.
Who?

93
00:06:31,689 --> 00:06:34,625
Sondra Pransky.
I'm the journalism
student from Adair.

94
00:06:34,692 --> 00:06:37,389
I wrote to you
about getting an interview
for the school newspaper.

95
00:06:37,461 --> 00:06:38,451
Oh...

96
00:06:38,562 --> 00:06:42,021
And you, well,
your secretary, actually,
because... Not you.

97
00:06:42,100 --> 00:06:44,500
I mean, I know how busy
film directors get and all.

98
00:06:44,569 --> 00:06:47,298
But you said
if I was in London visiting,
then you would, you know,

99
00:06:47,672 --> 00:06:49,697
and here I am,
which is fantastic.

100
00:06:49,908 --> 00:06:51,569
I think I have
your letter, actually.

101
00:06:51,709 --> 00:06:53,904
See, right now
I'm a bit tied up.
Here it is!

102
00:06:54,545 --> 00:06:56,480
Here it is.
This is so great for me.

103
00:06:56,548 --> 00:06:59,380
I mean, you've got
a huge following in Rochester.

104
00:06:59,451 --> 00:07:00,678
It gets very cold there.

105
00:07:00,786 --> 00:07:03,584
With your new movie
coming out in the fall,
and... Well...

106
00:07:03,822 --> 00:07:05,221
Actually,

107
00:07:05,990 --> 00:07:09,255
I was wondering
if we could just ask you
a couple of questions.

108
00:07:09,326 --> 00:07:12,694
Do you mind?
Okay, okay, but
we got to be real quick.

109
00:07:30,449 --> 00:07:32,713
SONDRA: I write
for the cultural part
of the paper.

110
00:07:32,783 --> 00:07:35,617
I'm looking to move into
more serious pieces.

111
00:07:35,987 --> 00:07:40,014
And when you say something
more serious, that's...

112
00:07:42,927 --> 00:07:44,360
You really want to know?

113
00:07:45,197 --> 00:07:47,630
Well, originally, I wasn't
going to go to college.

114
00:07:47,699 --> 00:07:50,725
I was going to become
a dental hygienist
like my sister, Beverly.

115
00:07:50,802 --> 00:07:52,894
And, don't get me wrong,
it's a great profession.

116
00:07:52,971 --> 00:07:56,428
I have very high respect
for teeth and gums,
particularly gums.

117
00:07:56,507 --> 00:07:57,941
My whole family's
in orthodontics. But...

118
00:07:58,009 --> 00:08:01,341
And what?
You're vacationing here?
Oh, yes.

119
00:08:01,545 --> 00:08:06,005
Oh, I'm just very friendly
with a very upper class
British family.

120
00:08:06,084 --> 00:08:08,143
Our families vacationed
in Palm Beach together.

121
00:08:08,220 --> 00:08:09,619
My mother
won a visit to Palm Beach

122
00:08:09,687 --> 00:08:12,213
and I became friends
with their granddaughter,
Vivian.

123
00:08:12,290 --> 00:08:13,951
She's so lovely.
She'll stay with us...

124
00:08:14,125 --> 00:08:16,593
Another?
Oh, thanks.

125
00:08:17,762 --> 00:08:21,163
So I slept with him
and I didn't even
get the interview.

126
00:08:21,233 --> 00:08:22,757
I mean,
what kind of a reporter am I?

127
00:08:22,901 --> 00:08:24,869
How was the sex?
Give me all the details.

128
00:08:24,935 --> 00:08:27,529
Who knows? I was so drunk,
I don't even remember.

129
00:08:27,838 --> 00:08:29,136
All I know is that
the second it was over,

130
00:08:29,206 --> 00:08:31,401
he got a phone call
and had to leave
suddenly for Thailand.

131
00:08:31,475 --> 00:08:32,465
Thailand?

132
00:08:32,543 --> 00:08:36,344
Yeah, Justin Richards
got fired from some project
and he had to take over.

133
00:08:36,413 --> 00:08:37,437
What difference does it make?

134
00:08:37,515 --> 00:08:39,177
The point is,
I told the whole school

135
00:08:39,250 --> 00:08:41,412
I'd get an exclusive
with Michael Tinsley!

136
00:08:41,485 --> 00:08:42,475
(LAUGHING)
You were nervous.

137
00:08:42,787 --> 00:08:44,754
You're inexperienced.
You drank.

138
00:08:44,822 --> 00:08:46,380
He's a charming genius.

139
00:08:46,524 --> 00:08:48,720
But you know,
you're a very attractive,
sexy girl.

140
00:08:48,793 --> 00:08:51,283
If you're going to interview
movers and shakers
in their hotel rooms,

141
00:08:51,363 --> 00:08:52,523
you better watch out.

142
00:08:52,596 --> 00:08:55,623
Not that I'd mind
a roll in the hay
with Michael Tinsley.

143
00:08:56,000 --> 00:08:58,834
I've put some fresh towels
in your bedroom, Sondra.

144
00:08:59,037 --> 00:09:00,333
SONDRA: Thank you,
Mrs. Thompson.

145
00:09:00,437 --> 00:09:03,100
Come on, sweetheart.
Chop, chop.
You're gonna be late.

146
00:09:03,207 --> 00:09:06,005
Oh, Mom.
SONDRA: The point is
I didn't get the story!

147
00:09:06,076 --> 00:09:07,806
I mean, if I'd used
my feminine wiles

148
00:09:07,879 --> 00:09:09,573
like Katharine Hepburn
or Rosalind Russell.

149
00:09:09,648 --> 00:09:11,013
Oh, come on.

150
00:09:11,115 --> 00:09:12,913
We'll go have lunch
at The Ivy,

151
00:09:12,984 --> 00:09:14,177
and then we'll take
my little brother

152
00:09:14,251 --> 00:09:16,048
to see that show
he's so excited about,

153
00:09:16,120 --> 00:09:17,918
and then we'll go
to that party tonight.

154
00:09:17,989 --> 00:09:19,889
There'll be
loads of gorgeous guys there.

155
00:09:19,957 --> 00:09:22,392
And you're always saying
all the men you meet
are complete losers.

156
00:09:22,527 --> 00:09:25,188
So you blew the story.
It's not life or death.

157
00:09:25,263 --> 00:09:26,287
(SIGHS)

158
00:09:26,498 --> 00:09:28,328
(TRITSCH-TRATSCH POLKA
PLAYING)

159
00:10:01,298 --> 00:10:03,460
M. C: Ladies and gentlemen,
prepare yourselves

160
00:10:03,534 --> 00:10:05,798
for the astonishing magic

161
00:10:05,870 --> 00:10:08,235
of Splendini!

162
00:10:08,639 --> 00:10:09,629
(ALL CHEERING)

163
00:10:36,634 --> 00:10:38,000
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

164
00:10:56,153 --> 00:10:58,178
Thank you,
ladies and gentlemen,
you're an incredible audience

165
00:10:58,255 --> 00:11:00,724
and I mean that sincerely.
I say that from
the bottom of my heart.

166
00:11:00,924 --> 00:11:03,654
You know, every time
I come to London,
this great city,

167
00:11:03,794 --> 00:11:05,695
I always get
a sincere sensation,

168
00:11:05,764 --> 00:11:09,130
because you're marvelous
people, beautiful humans.

169
00:11:09,500 --> 00:11:11,696
And for my next experiment...

170
00:11:11,769 --> 00:11:13,738
And I call it an experiment,
you see, not a trick.

171
00:11:13,871 --> 00:11:15,202
I'm gonna need a volunteer.

172
00:11:15,273 --> 00:11:17,571
So if you'll step out
and find someone for me.

173
00:11:17,642 --> 00:11:21,772
This is kind of dangerous
stuff so no children here.

174
00:11:21,846 --> 00:11:23,836
I need
a grown-up volunteer.

175
00:11:23,914 --> 00:11:26,349
Someone who's willing
to put her life on the line.

176
00:11:28,519 --> 00:11:30,783
(TRITSCH-TRATSCH POLKA
PLAYING)

177
00:11:33,224 --> 00:11:35,054
Is this
your first time on stage?
Yes.

178
00:11:35,192 --> 00:11:37,320
Yes, you've never done...
Well, you got nothing
to be afraid of.

179
00:11:37,394 --> 00:11:39,828
(STUTTERING)
You nervous? Don't be nervous.

180
00:11:40,164 --> 00:11:41,756
What's your name?
Tell them your name.

181
00:11:41,899 --> 00:11:42,923
Sondra Pransky.

182
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:46,027
(EXCLAIMS) A landsman!
United States! Fantastic!

183
00:11:46,104 --> 00:11:48,937
And where are you from,
Sondra? No, don't tell me,

184
00:11:49,073 --> 00:11:51,167
'cause I got a great ear
for that kind of thing.

185
00:11:51,241 --> 00:11:54,109
Alabama!
Am I right? Am I right?

186
00:11:54,178 --> 00:11:55,407
Close.
Yeah?

187
00:11:55,480 --> 00:11:57,879
I'm from Brooklyn.
Incredible!

188
00:11:57,948 --> 00:11:59,917
God bless you, sweetheart.
I'm from Brooklyn, too.

189
00:11:59,984 --> 00:12:02,611
That is fantastic.
I feel such love
coming from this woman.

190
00:12:02,721 --> 00:12:03,914
I can't tell you.
It's really...

191
00:12:04,022 --> 00:12:06,820
I say this with all sincerity
from the bottom of my heart.

192
00:12:06,890 --> 00:12:09,256
You're an incredible
human being and
a credit to your race.

193
00:12:09,527 --> 00:12:12,894
Sondra, let me ask you
a question. What do you do?
Tell them what you do.

194
00:12:13,697 --> 00:12:14,823
I'm a student.

195
00:12:14,999 --> 00:12:18,162
Yeah? A student?
And what are you studying?

196
00:12:18,302 --> 00:12:21,397
No. No, wait!
I got an instinct
for what a person is studying.

197
00:12:21,605 --> 00:12:24,096
For exactly
what you'd be right for.

198
00:12:24,174 --> 00:12:26,700
Dental hygienist!

199
00:12:26,778 --> 00:12:28,245
(ALL LAUGHING)
Was I close?

200
00:12:29,480 --> 00:12:30,947
No, I'm a journalism student.

201
00:12:31,014 --> 00:12:33,346
You study journalism.
Well, if you...

202
00:12:34,318 --> 00:12:36,378
Have you ever been
dematerialized before?

203
00:12:36,520 --> 00:12:39,216
No.
No? Well, there's nothing
to be afraid of.

204
00:12:39,289 --> 00:12:41,587
I'm just going to agitate
some of your molecules
and split them apart.

205
00:12:41,658 --> 00:12:43,286
It's not gonna hurt.
I just ate.
Is this gonna make me...

206
00:12:43,528 --> 00:12:45,519
You just ate.
She said she...

207
00:12:45,730 --> 00:12:47,629
I'll do the jokes, Sondra.

208
00:12:47,698 --> 00:12:50,793
Now, Sondra,
I'm going to ask you
to step into that box

209
00:12:51,235 --> 00:12:54,171
and I'm gonna have
your molecules split up.
I'm gonna split 'em up.

210
00:12:54,239 --> 00:12:56,673
It's gonna be very painless.
And I'm gonna put you
back together again.

211
00:12:56,740 --> 00:12:58,436
Don't tickle me.

212
00:12:58,676 --> 00:13:01,303
Tell them what
you just said to me.
You got to hear this.

213
00:13:01,379 --> 00:13:02,640
Tell them what you said to me.

214
00:13:02,780 --> 00:13:04,408
No, tell them, tell them.
(GIGGLES) No.

215
00:13:04,481 --> 00:13:06,472
She said, "Don't tickle me."

216
00:13:06,551 --> 00:13:08,313
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)
God bless you, sweetheart.

217
00:13:08,385 --> 00:13:10,250
You got
a fantastic sense of humor.

218
00:13:10,321 --> 00:13:12,515
You know if more people
in the world
had a sense of humor,

219
00:13:12,590 --> 00:13:14,854
we would not be
in the state we are in today.

220
00:13:14,926 --> 00:13:16,393
I kid you not.

221
00:13:16,461 --> 00:13:17,450
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

222
00:13:17,528 --> 00:13:18,518
(TRITSCH-TRATSCH POLKA
PLAYING)

223
00:13:18,696 --> 00:13:20,095
Get in the box.
Get in the box, Sondra.
Go ahead.

224
00:13:20,230 --> 00:13:22,927
In the box. Go ahead.
Get in the box.
Get in the box. Hurry up.

225
00:13:23,333 --> 00:13:26,326
I'm going to agitate
the molecules now.
Miss Sondra Mandelbaum.

226
00:13:26,437 --> 00:13:27,461
Pransky.

227
00:13:27,705 --> 00:13:29,001
Pransky, Mandelbaum.
What's the...

228
00:13:29,072 --> 00:13:31,336
We take off
the same holidays.
Doesn't matter.

229
00:13:31,408 --> 00:13:33,604
Get in the box, sweetheart,
and don't be scared.

230
00:13:33,677 --> 00:13:34,667
You in there?

231
00:13:38,182 --> 00:13:39,844
(GASPS)

232
00:13:39,918 --> 00:13:42,716
You're a journalist, right?
Oh, my God.
What are you doing in here?

233
00:13:42,787 --> 00:13:44,186
Aren't you
