00:24:29,467 --> 00:24:30,832
How can we meet him?

465
00:24:32,001 --> 00:24:34,197
(STUTTERING) I don't know.
They have a class system.

466
00:24:34,270 --> 00:24:36,898
He's an aristocrat,
and, you know,
we're commoners.

467
00:24:37,074 --> 00:24:40,907
In fact, according to his
system, I think we're probably
classified as scum.

468
00:24:41,479 --> 00:24:43,845
This is our only chance.
He's all alone.

469
00:24:44,381 --> 00:24:45,847
Well, you're
a pretty girl.

470
00:24:45,915 --> 00:24:49,407
You know, I think you could
probably get this guy
to get interested in you.

471
00:24:49,487 --> 00:24:52,182
Don't be silly.
Particularly if he's got
a twisted mind.

472
00:24:54,692 --> 00:24:56,886
Look, I can't
just go up to him and say,
"Hi, how are you?"

473
00:24:56,961 --> 00:24:59,987
I mean,
what if he gets suspicious,
or, you know,

474
00:25:00,064 --> 00:25:02,463
if he gets put off, or...

475
00:25:02,566 --> 00:25:03,555
Drown.

476
00:25:04,300 --> 00:25:06,894
What?
Drown! Drown!
I'll go get... I'll go get...

477
00:25:06,971 --> 00:25:08,268
(SCOFFS)
Listen to me!

478
00:25:08,338 --> 00:25:09,532
I'll go get coffee.

479
00:25:09,606 --> 00:25:12,541
Get a cramp,
go in the water,
flounder around,

480
00:25:12,609 --> 00:25:13,804
you know. Yes!

481
00:25:14,345 --> 00:25:17,007
Go ahead, sweetheart.
That's a great idea.

482
00:25:17,080 --> 00:25:19,777
He'll be obliged
to save you that way.

483
00:25:19,849 --> 00:25:22,875
And if he doesn't...
lf, you know...
Then I'll notify your parents.

484
00:25:53,349 --> 00:25:54,338
SONDRA: (GASPS) Help!

485
00:25:55,352 --> 00:25:57,047
(MUFFLED SCREAMING)

486
00:26:00,391 --> 00:26:01,380
Help!

487
00:26:04,394 --> 00:26:06,021
(SONDRA GASPING)

488
00:26:11,101 --> 00:26:13,261
(SONDRA COUGHING)
It's all right. Shh.

489
00:26:14,070 --> 00:26:16,231
It's okay.
There you go.

490
00:26:17,607 --> 00:26:19,200
Are you all right? Okay.

491
00:26:19,442 --> 00:26:20,432
I'm sorry.

492
00:26:20,577 --> 00:26:22,546
(COUGHING)
All right, here.
Here we are.

493
00:26:22,645 --> 00:26:24,579
Here we are. You all right?
Thank you.

494
00:26:24,882 --> 00:26:27,112
You okay?
Yes, thank you very much.

495
00:26:27,183 --> 00:26:28,946
Sorry.
It's my pleasure.
Here, let me help you out.

496
00:26:29,219 --> 00:26:30,208
(GRUNTS)

497
00:26:31,221 --> 00:26:32,847
I'm not a very good swimmer.

498
00:26:33,257 --> 00:26:34,587
(COUGHING)
It's all right.

499
00:26:34,692 --> 00:26:35,953
My leg cramped.

500
00:26:36,026 --> 00:26:37,084
Your leg?
Here, stretch it out.

501
00:26:37,161 --> 00:26:38,219
Oh.
That's it.

502
00:26:38,295 --> 00:26:39,557
Thank you.
No problem.

503
00:26:39,797 --> 00:26:42,230
Listen, you should always
do a little stretching
before you go in.

504
00:26:42,333 --> 00:26:44,857
You know,
that way you won't cramp.
Oh, thank you very much.

505
00:26:45,001 --> 00:26:47,470
I haven't been swimming
in so long.

506
00:26:48,137 --> 00:26:49,502
You're a new face.

507
00:26:49,839 --> 00:26:51,397
Have you
just become a member?

508
00:26:51,474 --> 00:26:53,875
Oh, no,
I'm a guest of the Fultons.

509
00:26:54,010 --> 00:26:56,205
Oh, right, Jack Fulton.
Yes, lovely chap.

510
00:26:56,614 --> 00:26:59,447
I'm Peter Lyman, by the way.
Hi, Son...

511
00:26:59,950 --> 00:27:00,939
Sond...

512
00:27:02,519 --> 00:27:03,644
Jade.

513
00:27:03,921 --> 00:27:05,115
Jade Spence.

514
00:27:05,388 --> 00:27:07,253
Jade Julliard Spence.

515
00:27:07,924 --> 00:27:10,222
That's a very pretty name.
Thank you.

516
00:27:10,361 --> 00:27:13,818
Yes, we're the Spences of...
Of Palm Beach.

517
00:27:14,298 --> 00:27:17,028
Oh, not the same Spences
who own the shipping line?

518
00:27:17,300 --> 00:27:18,632
No, no, no.

519
00:27:18,769 --> 00:27:22,671
My father's into
silver and gold

520
00:27:22,740 --> 00:27:24,673
and drilling.
Ah.

521
00:27:24,974 --> 00:27:26,032
For wells.

522
00:27:26,376 --> 00:27:28,402
What are you doing
in London?

523
00:27:28,912 --> 00:27:31,346
I'm here visiting friends
in Holland Park.

524
00:27:31,815 --> 00:27:33,645
Oh, good.
What do you do, Jade?

525
00:27:33,750 --> 00:27:36,515
Well, I am an actress.

526
00:27:36,586 --> 00:27:37,848
Oh, really?
Mmm-hmm.

527
00:27:38,122 --> 00:27:40,317
Yes, actually
I'm up for the part of Desiree

528
00:27:40,391 --> 00:27:42,415
in the new Mike Tinsley film.

529
00:27:42,492 --> 00:27:44,324
Oh, well, you're certainly
beautiful enough.

530
00:27:44,461 --> 00:27:46,052
(GIGGLING) Thank you.

531
00:27:46,195 --> 00:27:47,959
Look, Jade,

532
00:27:48,365 --> 00:27:49,423
if you're not busy,

533
00:27:49,500 --> 00:27:52,263
my father's giving
a garden party
at the estate on Sunday

534
00:27:52,336 --> 00:27:53,597
and I'd love you to come.

535
00:27:53,703 --> 00:27:56,798
I'd be very happy
to be your date
and show you around.

536
00:27:56,874 --> 00:27:59,740
The English countryside
is very lovely
this time of the year.

537
00:27:59,809 --> 00:28:01,971
Sounds fantastic.
Good.

538
00:28:02,078 --> 00:28:04,512
Do you mind
if I bring my father?

539
00:28:04,781 --> 00:28:06,078
Your father?

540
00:28:06,182 --> 00:28:08,276
Oh, look!
There he is right now.

541
00:28:08,751 --> 00:28:09,740
Ah.

542
00:28:09,920 --> 00:28:11,785
I was in the lounge.
I heard you drowning.

543
00:28:11,855 --> 00:28:15,051
I finished my tea and scones
and came immediately.

544
00:28:15,192 --> 00:28:16,853
SONDRA: Dad,
this is Peter Lyman,

545
00:28:16,926 --> 00:28:18,622
who was nice enough
to rescue me.

546
00:28:18,695 --> 00:28:19,684
Dad?

547
00:28:23,834 --> 00:28:25,563
Yes, of course, child!

548
00:28:25,635 --> 00:28:28,730
She cannot swim.
The girl cannot swim.

549
00:28:28,838 --> 00:28:32,001
Like a lead weight,
she sinks to the bottom
all the time.

550
00:28:32,142 --> 00:28:36,044
It's a family trait.
Lack of buoyancy, or...
Her siblings have it as well.

551
00:28:36,113 --> 00:28:38,980
Yes, well, listen,
pleasure to meet you,
Mr. Spence, right?

552
00:28:39,048 --> 00:28:40,073
Yes.

553
00:28:40,150 --> 00:28:42,549
Yes, and I'll see you
on Sunday at the estate.

554
00:28:42,618 --> 00:28:44,814
Oh, great.
Sunday? What's Sunday?
Not a fox hunt?

555
00:28:44,954 --> 00:28:47,947
(CHUCKLING)
No. No, Dad.
I'll explain it to you later.

556
00:28:48,092 --> 00:28:50,083
Listen, I'll leave
all the information
at the desk, all right?

557
00:28:50,160 --> 00:28:51,558
Hey, come, child.

558
00:28:53,797 --> 00:28:56,731
What kind of idiot are you?
Not a fox hunt?

559
00:28:56,834 --> 00:28:59,597
I'd like
to talk to these people
in their own terms.

560
00:28:59,802 --> 00:29:02,294
And, oh,
thanks for telling him
I'm your father.

561
00:29:02,439 --> 00:29:05,202
Oh, incidentally, he thinks
my name is Jade Spence,

562
00:29:05,275 --> 00:29:06,798
so that makes you
Mr. Spence.

563
00:29:06,876 --> 00:29:10,039
Wait a minute, I... This is
too tricky. I don't want to
go ahead with this.

564
00:29:10,213 --> 00:29:13,273
Why? What's wrong with you?
Your whole life is deception.
You're a magician.

565
00:29:13,383 --> 00:29:16,375
Yes, I'm a magician
and I want to stay a magician.
Can I have a Coke please?

566
00:29:16,452 --> 00:29:18,853
I don't want to get sued
or deported

567
00:29:18,922 --> 00:29:21,253
or arrested
for stalking somebody.

568
00:29:21,325 --> 00:29:23,451
This is a big guy
you're dealing with.

569
00:29:23,527 --> 00:29:26,325
This is a big story,
no kidding.
That's what Joe Strombel said.

570
00:29:26,395 --> 00:29:29,160
That's why he returned,
you know. This is
his last big scoop.

571
00:29:29,232 --> 00:29:30,461
Hey. What do I care
about Joe Strombel?

572
00:29:30,534 --> 00:29:34,230
Suddenly I'm taking direction
from a hunk of ectoplasm?

573
00:29:34,337 --> 00:29:36,271
This could be
very big for my career.

574
00:29:36,606 --> 00:29:40,337
Your career's fine.
You're on the college Bugle,
or whatever it is.

575
00:29:40,410 --> 00:29:42,001
You got years for scoops.

576
00:29:42,112 --> 00:29:43,703
You know what?
Forget you, all right.

577
00:29:43,780 --> 00:29:46,772
I'll do this on my own.
I don't need you.
Go back to your card tricks.

578
00:29:46,849 --> 00:29:48,613
I didn't say
I wouldn't help you.

579
00:29:48,684 --> 00:29:51,244
You know, I just...
It has to be done properly.

580
00:29:51,622 --> 00:29:53,646
You know, we gotta
put our heads together.

581
00:29:53,856 --> 00:29:56,723
If we put
our heads together,
you'll hear a hollow noise.

582
00:30:15,345 --> 00:30:17,676
Look at this place.
All it's missing is a moat.

583
00:30:22,685 --> 00:30:25,347
Ooh! Hey,
I could get used to this.

584
00:30:26,022 --> 00:30:27,250
Look at this.

585
00:30:29,226 --> 00:30:32,161
SONDRA: Oh, there he is.
Remember, Jade Spence.

586
00:30:32,362 --> 00:30:33,692
Jade...
Jade, who?

587
00:30:34,463 --> 00:30:36,295
(MUMBLING)

588
00:30:36,666 --> 00:30:38,066
Ah.
PETER: There you are.

589
00:30:38,134 --> 00:30:40,932
Hello.
How are you? Welcome,
Mr. Spence and Jade.

590
00:30:41,003 --> 00:30:42,163
Mr. Spence.

591
00:30:42,239 --> 00:30:45,674
You look stunning. Stunning.
Oh, thank you.
It's beautiful here.

592
00:30:45,741 --> 00:30:46,834
Thank you. Thank you. Yes.

593
00:30:46,910 --> 00:30:49,401
It's been in the family
for years. About 400 years.

594
00:30:49,512 --> 00:30:51,413
It's a little stuffy
for my taste, but...
Oh.

595
00:30:51,480 --> 00:30:53,778
She said,
"All that's missing
is a moat."

596
00:30:53,916 --> 00:30:56,885
Right.
(CHUCKLES) I love that.
I love the moat line.

597
00:30:56,953 --> 00:30:59,980
"All that's missing
is a moat." Beautiful.
Ah, this is my father.

598
00:31:00,257 --> 00:31:02,520
Father, Stephen Lyman,
this is... These are
my friends from America

599
00:31:02,593 --> 00:31:03,923
I was telling you about.
Oh, Lord Lyman.

600
00:31:04,027 --> 00:31:05,016
Jade Spence, Mr. Spence.

601
00:31:05,194 --> 00:31:06,627
How are you?
Hello.

602
00:31:06,696 --> 00:31:09,996
Curtsey, curtsey, curtsey,
curtsey, curtsey, curtsey,
I've never met a Lord before.

603
00:31:10,067 --> 00:31:11,159
How exciting!

604
00:31:11,234 --> 00:31:14,067
No, but there was
that Earl that we...
There was that Earl.

605
00:31:14,203 --> 00:31:15,865
I do hope
you're enjoying yourself.

606
00:31:15,939 --> 00:31:17,873
Peter, why don't you
show them around?

607
00:31:18,008 --> 00:31:19,474
Absolutely.
Would you like that?

608
00:31:19,609 --> 00:31:21,634
Oh, it...
Charmed, I'm sure.

609
00:31:21,778 --> 00:31:24,008
Should we hit
the buffet table first though?

610
00:31:24,080 --> 00:31:25,445
No, Dad.
Because the stuff
looks great.

611
00:31:25,515 --> 00:31:27,005
Remember,
we wanted to look around.

612
00:31:27,084 --> 00:31:28,914
(CHUCKLING)
Yes, of course, of course,
blessed offspring.

613
00:31:28,986 --> 00:31:31,284
Why don't we get a drink
and then we'll start inside?

614
00:31:31,454 --> 00:31:32,854
SONDRA: Oh, okay.
Come.

615
00:31:37,627 --> 00:31:40,461
Yes, I love this room here.
We often spend
evenings in here.

616
00:31:40,564 --> 00:31:42,054
The English countryside!

617
00:31:42,231 --> 00:31:45,394
It's elegant,
yet understated. I like that.

618
00:31:45,535 --> 00:31:47,001
You've done wonders
with the place.

619
00:31:47,203 --> 00:31:48,830
(CHUCKLES)
It brings to mind Trollope.

620
00:31:49,072 --> 00:31:50,868
Oh, do you enjoy
reading Trollope, too?

621
00:31:51,008 --> 00:31:53,499
No, no, not the author.
This was a girl I knew.

622
00:31:53,943 --> 00:31:56,741
Well, come. Let's go upstairs
and have a look at the view.

623
00:31:56,813 --> 00:31:57,801
Oh.

624
00:31:57,948 --> 00:32:00,609
Would you quit fooling around!
What's wrong with you?

625
00:32:00,717 --> 00:32:02,809
Try to pick up clues,
try to remember things.
I'm charming him.

626
00:32:02,885 --> 00:32:05,354
I remember. I got
a mnemonic system that I use.

627
00:32:05,454 --> 00:32:07,445
I use images, it's a trick.
Uh-huh, yeah.

628
00:32:07,557 --> 00:32:09,047
Say I want to remember
this ashtray.

629
00:32:09,125 --> 00:32:13,357
I think of, like, 50 ashtrays
dancing on a desert island
in hula skirts or something

630
00:32:13,596 --> 00:32:15,723
and then I remember.
I can call it
to mind whenever I...

631
00:32:15,798 --> 00:32:17,198
Where are you going?

632
00:32:17,567 --> 00:32:19,535
This is
one of the drawing rooms.

633
00:32:19,769 --> 00:32:21,931
Wow, this is
really beautiful, isn't it?

634
00:32:22,005 --> 00:32:24,303
Oh, here we have...
This is my great-grandfather.

635
00:32:24,407 --> 00:32:27,308
There's grandfather
and his wife, Lady Hayden.

636
00:32:27,376 --> 00:32:30,539
Reminds me of
the portrait of Aunt Hillary
in the library, no?

637
00:32:30,980 --> 00:32:35,280
Game woman, Hillary.
Suffragette, I believe.
Yeah. Diphtheria took her.

638
00:32:35,585 --> 00:32:38,212
Or perhaps it was elm blight.

639
00:32:38,855 --> 00:32:40,048
Come on, Dad.

640
00:32:40,958 --> 00:32:42,755
SONDRA: Oh,
this is just beautiful. Wow.

641
00:32:42,826 --> 00:32:45,351
Yes. I love the lake.
Do either of you fish?

642
00:32:45,429 --> 00:32:47,521
No, no, never have.
Oh, I'll have to teach you.

643
00:32:47,730 --> 00:32:50,028
I've taken some salmon,
you know. Organic.

644
00:32:50,232 --> 00:32:52,792
Yes, me, too.
I fly fish a little. But...

645
00:32:53,569 --> 00:32:55,162
So, Jade, do you
enjoy concerts?

646
00:32:55,238 --> 00:32:56,932
I'm very big
on the Philharmonic.

647
00:32:57,007 --> 00:32:58,405
We sponsor, in fact.

648
00:32:58,474 --> 00:33:00,602
I used to play the violin,
very, very badly.

649
00:33:00,844 --> 00:33:05,212
But I have a number of...
Well, actually quite a large
musical collection.

650
00:33:05,281 --> 00:33:06,977
Do you play an instrument,
either of you?

651
00:33:07,049 --> 00:33:08,346
Because we have
these lovely music gatherings.

652
00:33:08,417 --> 00:33:09,612
I do. Yes, I play the...

653
00:33:09,685 --> 00:33:10,674
(GRUNTS)

654
00:33:11,288 --> 00:33:14,222
Various classics,
you know, Noel Coward
and Shakespeare and...

655
00:33:14,758 --> 00:33:18,090
Right.
We gave her piano lessons
when she was a little girl,

656
00:33:18,161 --> 00:33:20,959
but her fingers
were just too stubby. So...

657
00:33:21,565 --> 00:33:23,294
Yes, what about you,
Mr. Spence?

658
00:33:23,733 --> 00:33:25,291
Well, I play the blues harp.

659
00:33:25,501 --> 00:33:27,731
It's a little metal thing
you put in your mouth

660
00:33:27,871 --> 00:33:30,101
and makes a twanging sound.
Very musical.
Yes, yes.

661
00:33:30,173 --> 00:33:33,403
Used to be called
the Jew's harp, but you know
how those people are.

662
00:33:33,477 --> 00:33:36,070
The slightest hint
of anti-Semitism
and they write letters.

663
00:33:36,278 --> 00:33:39,645
I would love it if you could
teach me how to fly fish.
That would be great.

664
00:33:39,715 --> 00:33:40,910
Oh, it would be my pleasure.

665
00:33:42,251 --> 00:33:45,482
Okay, I want you to
watch me very closely. Pay
very strict attention here.

666
00:33:45,622 --> 00:33:47,055
Now I want you
to take a card.

667
00:33:47,124 --> 00:33:48,614
Take any card you like.
You got it?

668
00:33:48,692 --> 00:33:50,386
Go ahead, sweetheart. Take it.
You got it?
Mmm-hmm.

669
00:33:50,460 --> 00:33:52,086
Now put it
in your pocketbook.
Put the card...

670
00:33:52,162 --> 00:33:53,355
She's gonna put the card
in her pocketbook.

671
00:33:53,430 --> 00:33:55,557
You got it? All right,
now tell everybody
what the card was.

672
00:33:55,999 --> 00:33:57,489
It was the six of hearts.
Six of hearts.

673
00:33:57,634 --> 00:33:58,623
Can I ask you a question?

674
00:33:58,701 --> 00:34:00,727
Was it
this six of hearts?

675
00:34:01,070 --> 00:34:02,265
But I just put that
in my bag.

676
00:34:02,338 --> 00:34:04,568
Well, check your card.
Check your card.

677
00:34:05,275 --> 00:34:06,263
It's amazing!

678
00:34:07,109 --> 00:34:08,771
You're
a wonderful sport, Claire.

679
00:34:08,844 --> 00:34:10,574
I mean that sincerely.
God bless you.

680
00:34:10,646 --> 00:34:13,047
You're a very sweet woman,
and this has been
a great group.

681
00:34:13,150 --> 00:34:16,313
From the bottom of my heart,
I say this with
all due respect.

682
00:34:16,552 --> 00:34:19,989
You're a wonderful... A credit
to your race and a
magnificent group of people.

683
00:34:20,056 --> 00:34:22,820
You know,
I must find out who
does the hedges here.

684
00:34:22,893 --> 00:34:24,588
Back home,
my topiary moose

685
00:34:24,661 --> 00:34:26,958
is starting
to look a little shabby
around the antlers.

686
00:34:27,030 --> 00:34:28,827
(LAUGHING) What do you do,
Mr. Spence?

687
00:34:28,898 --> 00:34:30,798
(STUTTERING) Me?
I'm in real estate.

688
00:34:31,134 --> 00:34:32,567
I'm sorry, I'm in oil!
I'm in oil.

689
00:34:32,635 --> 00:34:34,297
(STUTTERING) I was in
real estate,

690
00:34:34,371 --> 00:34:39,206
but, you know, land is
so difficult to come by now,
especially outdoors.

691
00:34:39,275 --> 00:34:40,436
It's become a problem.

692
00:34:40,510 --> 00:34:43,172
Incidentally,
I accept your invitation.

693
