from the Tarot deck."

819
00:40:49,077 --> 00:40:52,570
Hey, what time did you say
Peter arrived at the
poker game last night?

820
00:40:52,949 --> 00:40:56,077
If you're asking me,
did he have time
to strangle somebody

821
00:40:56,152 --> 00:40:58,746
and make the card game,
yes, he had plenty of time.

822
00:40:59,989 --> 00:41:02,286
I got to let
my feelings subside

823
00:41:02,358 --> 00:41:04,326
and probe deeper
into this case.

824
00:41:04,494 --> 00:41:05,791
What does that mean?

825
00:41:06,195 --> 00:41:09,255
Well, it means that we know
where his family lives,
we know his social circle,

826
00:41:09,331 --> 00:41:12,824
but we don't know
what his house looks like.
I want to get a look at that.

827
00:41:19,608 --> 00:41:20,802
PETER: Here we are.

828
00:41:24,047 --> 00:41:26,641
Wow.
This is really nice.
Thank you. Yes.

829
00:41:27,951 --> 00:41:29,418
Do you do
a lot of entertaining?

830
00:41:29,518 --> 00:41:31,452
I'm embarrassed
to say that I do.

831
00:41:31,521 --> 00:41:34,217
You must think
I'm an empty socialite.
Much of it's political.

832
00:41:34,289 --> 00:41:36,485
Oh, no.
I think you're swell.

833
00:41:40,096 --> 00:41:41,653
SONDRA:
That's a lovely painting.

834
00:41:42,699 --> 00:41:46,396
Oh, I recognize that
from my art history books.

835
00:41:46,469 --> 00:41:47,936
PETER: Oh, really?
Yes. Henry Moore.

836
00:41:48,003 --> 00:41:50,733
In fact, it was a present
from Henry Moore to my father.

837
00:41:51,507 --> 00:41:55,273
Oh, it's very beautiful.
Is it Roman, or Greek,
or something like that?

838
00:41:55,378 --> 00:41:59,405
It's Roman, in fact.
Second century A.D.

839
00:41:59,481 --> 00:42:00,813
You have good taste.

840
00:42:01,251 --> 00:42:02,809
I think you'll like
what's downstairs.

841
00:42:02,885 --> 00:42:05,012
The real treasures.
Come.
Oh.

842
00:42:17,367 --> 00:42:19,300
(SECURITY SYSTEM BEEPING)

843
00:42:25,742 --> 00:42:27,369
Here we are.

844
00:42:27,443 --> 00:42:28,431
Oh.

845
00:42:28,610 --> 00:42:32,876
These are all of
my instruments. The room
is climate controlled, it's

846
00:42:33,983 --> 00:42:36,610
to protect
all these beautiful pieces.

847
00:42:36,786 --> 00:42:38,686
It's fantastic.
Thank you. Thank you.

848
00:42:38,755 --> 00:42:40,416
Yes, my family's been
collecting it for years.

849
00:42:40,523 --> 00:42:44,050
This is a Guarneri.
And a Stradivarius.
You may have heard of them.

850
00:42:44,126 --> 00:42:46,561
Oh, you play these violins?
Oh, me? God, no. No, no.

851
00:42:46,862 --> 00:42:50,059
But we lend them out.
They need to be played.

852
00:42:52,168 --> 00:42:55,193
All these old instruments,
it's very romantic.

853
00:43:00,742 --> 00:43:03,302
Shall I show you upstairs?
Okay.

854
00:43:07,282 --> 00:43:08,614
(ALL CHEERING)

855
00:43:10,652 --> 00:43:12,746
SID: (STUTTERING)
What's your name, sweetheart?
Tell me your name.

856
00:43:12,822 --> 00:43:14,186
I'm Wendy Beamish.

857
00:43:14,257 --> 00:43:16,623
Wendy... Let's hear it
for Wendy Beamish.

858
00:43:17,960 --> 00:43:20,521
Fantastic. I love you, Wendy.
I really do.

859
00:43:20,663 --> 00:43:22,221
Is it your first time
on stage?
Yes. Yes.

860
00:43:22,331 --> 00:43:25,563
I love this woman
from the bottom of my heart.
I mean that sincerely.

861
00:43:25,702 --> 00:43:29,934
You're an incredible woman
and I say that
with all due respect, Wendy.

862
00:43:30,139 --> 00:43:32,902
Wendy, have you ever been
dematerialized before?
No, I haven't.

863
00:43:32,976 --> 00:43:35,467
Ever had your
molecules broken up?
No, no, I've haven't.

864
00:43:35,878 --> 00:43:38,244
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)
She's nervous.
Don't be nervous, sweetheart.

865
00:43:38,313 --> 00:43:39,871
This is not gonna hurt much.

866
00:43:39,949 --> 00:43:42,509
Get into the box.
Get into the dematerializer.

867
00:43:42,585 --> 00:43:44,815
Are you in there?
You comfortable?
I'm fine.

868
00:43:44,887 --> 00:43:47,219
Okay, okay, stay calm.
Stay calm.

869
00:43:47,789 --> 00:43:50,623
Can you hear me, Wendy?
