925
00:47:35,617 --> 00:47:37,608
(STUTTERING) Yeah,
but not a hooker?

926
00:47:39,889 --> 00:47:41,652
No, Sidney,
she's not a hooker!

927
00:47:41,757 --> 00:47:44,282
I hardly think so.
She's practically royalty.

928
00:47:44,527 --> 00:47:46,653
Christ,
you amaze me sometimes.
Your brain!

929
00:47:46,728 --> 00:47:50,027
(STUTTERING)
Back off. You know,
you're getting so upset.

930
00:47:50,099 --> 00:47:54,034
I'm just trying
to figure out
the various ramifications.

931
00:47:54,103 --> 00:47:55,297
I just don't like
this whole thing!

932
00:47:55,371 --> 00:47:57,565
I feel disgusting,
all right, it's awful.

933
00:47:57,739 --> 00:47:59,172
I don't like
the whole process.

934
00:47:59,242 --> 00:48:00,641
Yeah, you want to think
he's innocent.

935
00:48:00,710 --> 00:48:02,177
What's so bad about that, huh?

936
00:48:02,277 --> 00:48:04,541
Jesus, this guy
must be some lover, you know.

937
00:48:04,614 --> 00:48:07,411
I mean, all of a sudden
you're ready to dump
the whole story.

938
00:48:07,483 --> 00:48:10,213
I must find out
what breakfast cereal he eats.

939
00:48:11,721 --> 00:48:13,688
What am I talking about?
There's a combination
on the door

940
00:48:13,755 --> 00:48:16,554
where he keeps his precious
musical instruments.

941
00:48:16,759 --> 00:48:18,021
Okay,
so there is a combination!

942
00:48:18,094 --> 00:48:20,119
I just got
to get in that room.

943
00:48:20,195 --> 00:48:21,492
Do you have the combination?

944
00:48:21,563 --> 00:48:23,793
We're not gonna break
into his room if that's
what you're thinking.

945
00:48:23,865 --> 00:48:25,958
You gotta have the com...
I got to get in there.
No, no.

946
00:48:26,135 --> 00:48:28,728
No, no, we're not
going to do this because
it's not legal... You...

947
00:48:29,237 --> 00:48:30,670
Sondra, what's wrong with you?

948
00:48:30,739 --> 00:48:32,798
This guy is
the son of a Lord!

949
00:48:32,875 --> 00:48:37,175
They'll take us to
the Tower of London
and behead us!

950
00:48:39,481 --> 00:48:40,847
Hi.
VIVIAN: Guess what?

951
00:48:41,349 --> 00:48:43,545
What?
Peter Lyman sent you flowers.

952
00:48:43,786 --> 00:48:45,878
I assume your name
is Jade Spence?

953
00:48:46,054 --> 00:48:48,250
Naturally I accepted for you.

954
00:48:48,324 --> 00:48:49,483
Yeah, I'm Jade Spence.

955
00:48:49,557 --> 00:48:51,719
What is going on?
Oh, Vivian...

956
00:48:53,829 --> 00:48:54,818
Oh,

957
00:48:55,764 --> 00:48:58,199
Peter's giving a party
on Saturday and
he wants me to come.

958
00:48:58,266 --> 00:49:01,065
I... Oh, I guess
I'll have to buy a dress.

959
00:49:01,137 --> 00:49:02,865
Well, he certainly
seems smitten with you.

960
00:49:02,972 --> 00:49:04,963
If he's smitten with anyone,
it's Jade Spence.

961
00:49:05,106 --> 00:49:06,574
Who is Jade Spence?

962
00:49:06,742 --> 00:49:08,572
A would-be
investigative reporter

963
00:49:08,643 --> 00:49:11,476
who's falling in love
with the object
of her investigation.

964
00:49:14,951 --> 00:49:16,315
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

965
00:49:21,090 --> 00:49:22,614
Of course we did.
Absolutely.

966
00:49:22,692 --> 00:49:24,420
God bless you, sir.
I'm going to show you
a little thing.

967
00:49:24,492 --> 00:49:27,018
I want you
to think of a card. Just think
of one of those cards.

968
00:49:27,128 --> 00:49:28,391
Any one you want.
You got it?

969
00:49:28,463 --> 00:49:31,432
All right, now, are you
happening to be thinking
of the seven of spades?

970
00:49:32,702 --> 00:49:36,603
That's amazing!
How do you do that?
Just a little hobby of mine.

971
00:49:36,672 --> 00:49:38,606
You know, I wish
I had more time to practice,

972
00:49:38,907 --> 00:49:41,103
but, what with my oil wells,
you know, I never
get around to it.

973
00:49:41,177 --> 00:49:42,735
Your daughter's
very beautiful.

974
00:49:42,811 --> 00:49:44,210
You met my daughter?
Yes.

975
00:49:44,280 --> 00:49:47,545
Yes, we're very proud of her.
She's a lovely girl.
Overcame a great handicap.

976
00:49:47,615 --> 00:49:49,811
Yeah. You know, she was
learning disabled.

977
00:49:50,186 --> 00:49:52,585
Her mother and I took
her to many specialists,
you know.

978
00:49:52,655 --> 00:49:54,282
Now she's practically normal,
you know.

979
00:49:54,356 --> 00:49:55,688
She's a charmer.

980
00:49:55,925 --> 00:49:58,916
God bless you, sweetheart.
What is your sign?
I'm an Aquarian.

981
00:49:59,027 --> 00:50:01,018
You're Aquarian?
And what is your persuasion?

982
00:50:01,429 --> 00:50:03,829
Do you mean my religion?
Yeah, your persuasion.

983
00:50:03,898 --> 00:50:05,730
I'm a Christian. What are you?
Yes, are you?

984
00:50:05,835 --> 00:50:08,929
(STUTTERING)
Me, I was born into
the Hebrew persuasion,

985
00:50:09,005 --> 00:50:11,735
but, when I got older,
I converted to narcissism.

986
00:50:11,806 --> 00:50:12,898
Dad?
Hmm?

987
00:50:14,076 --> 00:50:16,067
Dad, I need
to talk to you right now.

988
00:50:16,144 --> 00:50:19,478
Oh, I was just about
to pull some quarters
out of Mrs. Quincy's nose.

989
00:50:19,614 --> 00:50:21,309
Right now.
I need to talk to you.

990
00:50:21,416 --> 00:50:22,405
Really?
Yep.

991
00:50:22,485 --> 00:50:24,146
Excuse me. I'll...

992
00:50:24,219 --> 00:50:25,380
Where?

993
00:50:27,523 --> 00:50:29,320
Would you stop doing
those nitwit tricks?

994
00:50:29,391 --> 00:50:31,690
What is wrong with you?
You're supposed to be
a dignified businessman.

995
00:50:31,760 --> 00:50:34,695
I told them it was a hobby.
The hobby of a rich merchant.

996
00:50:34,764 --> 00:50:35,788
You know, so...

997
00:50:35,864 --> 00:50:38,128
Oh, excuse me.
Excuse me.

998
00:50:38,934 --> 00:50:41,994
Go down the stairs,
open the music room door.
I'll keep Peter busy.

999
00:50:42,070 --> 00:50:44,505
I'll meet you down there
in a minute. You brought
the combination, right?

1000
00:50:44,572 --> 00:50:46,164
No, I left it
in my other jacket.

1001
00:50:46,242 --> 00:50:47,402
What?
Yes. And...

1002
00:50:47,476 --> 00:50:49,501
So, what are we gonna do?
You gotta go home
and get it then.

1003
00:50:49,577 --> 00:50:52,570
I can't get it
because the other
jacket's in the cleaners.

1004
00:50:52,648 --> 00:50:54,980
Sidney.
This is the problem
having a limited wardrobe.

1005
00:50:55,050 --> 00:50:56,313
But not to worry.

1006
00:50:56,385 --> 00:50:59,286
I have a mnemonic system.
I remember everything.

1007
00:50:59,355 --> 00:51:02,483
There you are. Mr. Spence,
trust you're having
a good time?

1008
00:51:02,557 --> 00:51:05,391
(STUTTERING) Yes,
a great time! This
reminds me of our party.

1009
00:51:05,460 --> 00:51:08,862
We threw a masked ball in
Palm Beach this year,
it was wonderful.

1010
00:51:08,931 --> 00:51:12,389
I came as a harlequin.
She dressed as Petunia Pig.

1011
00:51:12,467 --> 00:51:14,436
Honey, there's something
I wanted to ask you about.
Absolutely.

1012
00:51:14,503 --> 00:51:18,496
That was a mask, wasn't it?
Just... I love her.
Just a minute, okay?

1013
00:51:18,773 --> 00:51:21,742
Do you need a drink,
Mr. Spence?
No, I'm fine, thank you.

1014
00:51:43,932 --> 00:51:47,266
(STAMMERING) It's eight

1015
00:51:47,603 --> 00:51:50,594
blue horses.
No, no, no.

1016
00:51:50,940 --> 00:51:54,137
It's 10.
Ten spinning midgets.

1017
00:51:54,210 --> 00:51:58,202
No, it's 12.
Twelve jet planes
and eight... No.

1018
00:51:59,614 --> 00:52:01,139
(ALL CHATTERING)

1019
00:52:02,518 --> 00:52:05,851
Good to see you.
Have a nice time.
Nice to meet you.

1020
00:52:06,889 --> 00:52:09,722
Calm down, calm down.
It was... It was...

1021
00:52:09,824 --> 00:52:11,849
It was...

1022
00:52:11,994 --> 00:52:15,293
(STUTTERING)
Eight maids a-milking

1023
00:52:15,463 --> 00:52:18,398
and three French hens.

1024
00:52:18,766 --> 00:52:19,755
No, no.

1025
00:52:20,335 --> 00:52:21,666
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

1026
00:52:28,244 --> 00:52:31,907
Sixteen, wait, 20 jet planes,

1027
00:52:32,313 --> 00:52:34,248
12 spinning midgets.

1028
00:52:35,117 --> 00:52:37,016
(CHUCKLING) Eureka!

1029
00:53:12,387 --> 00:53:13,911
(LOCK BEEPING)

1030
00:53:24,934 --> 00:53:27,494
I'll be right back.
I'm just gonna
use the bathroom.

1031
00:53:45,153 --> 00:53:46,143
Sidney?

1032
00:53:46,255 --> 00:53:49,155
(THUMPING)
Sidney, is that you?

1033
00:53:49,391 --> 00:53:52,621
SID: I'm locked in!
Oh, Christ...
What's the combination?

1034
00:53:53,795 --> 00:53:55,730
For some reason,
it's gone out of my mind.

1035
00:53:55,864 --> 00:53:56,853
(SIGHS)

1036
00:53:58,166 --> 00:53:59,690
Did you see Miss Spence?

1037
00:53:59,768 --> 00:54:02,760
I thought I saw her
going downstairs.
Downstairs, right.

1038
00:54:03,706 --> 00:54:05,469
(STUTTERING) It's
16 blue horses.

1039
00:54:05,740 --> 00:54:09,472
It's 21 jet planes.

1040
00:54:09,612 --> 00:54:13,070
And 12 midgets.

1041
00:54:13,248 --> 00:54:14,614
Twelve spinning midgets.

1042
00:54:15,251 --> 00:54:16,809
(LOCK BEEPING)

1043
00:54:19,255 --> 00:54:20,278
Oh, thank God!

1044
00:54:20,356 --> 00:54:22,516
I thought
I was gonna turn out to be
one of those skeletons

1045
00:54:22,590 --> 00:54:24,922
people find
when they sell the house.
Check the door.

1046
00:54:24,994 --> 00:54:28,190
Sixteen, 21, 12.
You couldn't remember
that number?

1047
00:54:28,264 --> 00:54:31,824
My mnemonic system failed me.
What do you want me to say?

1048
00:54:32,134 --> 00:54:36,092
Now exactly
what are we looking for
in here? This is all...

1049
00:54:36,170 --> 00:54:37,728
I'm not really sure.

1050
00:54:38,139 --> 00:54:39,731
You're not sure?

1051
00:54:39,942 --> 00:54:41,465
Well, you know,
don't break anything.

1052
00:54:41,577 --> 00:54:44,568
By God, we'll get caught
and God knows.

1053
00:54:44,913 --> 00:54:46,402
Hey, you know
the old dirty joke

1054
00:54:46,481 --> 00:54:49,110
about how
the French horn player
sleeps with his wife at night?

1055
00:54:49,251 --> 00:54:51,115
Sidney,
put that thing down!

1056
00:54:52,186 --> 00:54:53,449
Will you excuse me?

1057
00:54:57,358 --> 00:54:59,657
There's nothing
but musical instruments
in here.

1058
00:54:59,728 --> 00:55:01,922
I'm telling you,
we're on a wild goose chase.
Believe me.

1059
00:55:01,996 --> 00:55:03,987
PETER: Jade?
What's the matter?

1060
00:55:04,099 --> 00:55:05,827
Did you hear that?

1061
00:55:06,101 --> 00:55:09,195
I thought I heard something.
Oh, come on, come on.
Let's get out of here.

1062
00:55:09,338 --> 00:55:11,271
All we need
is to get caught in here.

1063
00:55:13,208 --> 00:55:14,197
Jade?

1064
00:55:15,643 --> 00:55:17,407
Ah, there you are.
I was searching for you.

1065
00:55:17,478 --> 00:55:19,070
The guests
will be leaving soon.

1066
00:55:19,248 --> 00:55:22,614
Yes, well, I was
just showing Father around.
He loves English homes.

1067
00:55:22,751 --> 00:55:24,411
Yes, I was very impressed
with your cellar.

1068
00:55:24,485 --> 00:55:26,715
I have
a wonderful cellar myself.

1069
00:55:26,789 --> 00:55:29,849
No wine,
but it's rodent free.

1070
00:55:30,358 --> 00:55:31,826
PETER: (CHUCKLING) Well,
let's get a drink.

1071
00:55:31,893 --> 00:55:34,260
Please, Mr. Spence,
I haven't seen you
with a drink all night.

1072
00:55:34,730 --> 00:55:36,288
Can you stay the night,
please?
What?

1073
00:55:36,597 --> 00:55:37,826
Come on.
No, I can't.

1074
00:55:37,900 --> 00:55:39,594
Why not?
My father.

1075
00:55:39,668 --> 00:55:41,693
Oh, come on, I'll have
my driver take him home.

1076
00:55:41,769 --> 00:55:43,601
No.
I can't let you go.
You're too beautiful.

1077
00:55:43,739 --> 00:55:45,764
(MOANING)
Look at you. I can't.

1078
00:57:00,449 --> 00:57:02,177
(SIGHING)

1079
00:57:40,456 --> 00:57:41,547
Jade?

1080
00:57:49,030 --> 00:57:50,259
SONDRA: Oh.
Jade.

1081
00:57:52,266 --> 00:57:54,326
Jade, it's 4:00 a.m.

1082
00:57:54,436 --> 00:57:55,902
What are you doing?

1083
00:57:56,405 --> 00:57:58,429
I couldn't sleep,

1084
00:57:58,507 --> 00:58:01,442
so I thought
maybe some milk.

1085
00:58:01,943 --> 00:58:02,932
Hmm.

1086
00:58:05,481 --> 00:58:07,539
Jade, can I ask you something?
Mmm-hmm.

1087
00:58:10,853 --> 00:58:13,686
Would you consider
not going home at the end
of the summer?

1088
00:58:15,157 --> 00:58:17,523
SID: I don't understand,
what more proof do you need?

1089
00:58:17,592 --> 00:58:18,992
What are you gonna tell
the police?

1090
00:58:19,161 --> 00:58:21,856
The guy
owns a deck of Tarot cards.
That's not a crime.

1091
00:58:22,197 --> 00:58:23,994
I mean, what, he was late
for a poker game?

1092
00:58:24,065 --> 00:58:26,295
I'm sure he's smart enough
to have an alibi.

1093
00:58:26,434 --> 00:58:29,130
What are we left with?
His mother has
short-cut, brunette hair.

1094
00:58:29,204 --> 00:58:31,103
I mean, look,
if we blow the whistle
on this guy...

1095
00:58:31,172 --> 00:58:33,641
I know. I understand.
...and he's innocent
and we can't make the story...

1096
00:58:33,708 --> 00:58:35,438
Then he realizes
that you're, you know,

1097
00:58:35,510 --> 00:58:38,536
you're a pushy little phony
who's been playing him
for a sucker

1098
00:58:38,614 --> 00:58:40,980
and he dumps you,
you know. I get it.

1099
00:58:41,048 --> 00:58:43,313
All right. All I'm saying,
is that in order to make
an accusation,

1100
00:58:43,385 --> 00:58:44,409
we gotta have proof.

1101
00:58:44,519 --> 00:58:46,920
Especially
about Lord Lyman's son.

1102
00:58:47,088 --> 00:58:49,148
You don't make an accusation.

1103
00:58:49,224 --> 00:58:51,556
We can phone in
an anonymous tip.

1104
00:58:51,726 --> 00:58:54,251
You know how many crank tips
the papers say the police get?

1105
00:58:54,329 --> 00:58:56,297
You're gonna phone one in
on Peter Lyman!

1106
00:58:56,364 --> 00:58:58,389
They'll hang up on you
mid-sentence.

1107
00:58:58,934 --> 00:59:00,161
Besides,
if the story's true,

1108
00:59:00,235 --> 00:59:01,668
I want to be the one
to break it.

1109
00:59:01,737 --> 00:59:03,170
You know
what Joe Strombel said?

1110
00:59:03,271 --> 00:59:05,672
He said,
"Get it first,
but first get it right."

1111
00:59:07,242 --> 00:59:08,367
Happy birthday.

1112
00:59:09,911 --> 00:59:11,402
Wow, thank you.

1113
00:59:12,246 --> 00:59:13,907
What's up?
You look so sullen.

1114
00:59:14,782 --> 00:59:16,978
No, I'm not. I just...

1115
00:59:19,021 --> 00:59:20,681
I get sad around birthdays.

1116
00:59:20,755 --> 00:59:22,690
Oh, yes, well,
I can understand that,

1117
00:59:22,757 --> 00:59:25,192
but I think we're both
still young enough
to enjoy the gifts.

1118
00:59:25,260 --> 00:59:26,351
Come on, open it.

1119
00:59:26,994 --> 00:59:27,983
Okay.

1120
00:59:30,699 --> 00:59:32,666
Oh, wow, it's beautiful.

1121
00:59:32,768 --> 00:59:34,201
You like it?
I love it.

1122
00:59:34,268 --> 00:59:35,702
Good. Here, allow me.

1123
00:59:36,704 --> 00:59:37,693
Gosh.

1124
00:59:39,173 --> 00:59:40,606
You shouldn't have.

1125
00:59:40,675 --> 00:59:41,802
I wanted to.

1126
00:59:42,411 --> 00:59:46,643
Hey, hey,
are you crying?
No, I'm too tough to cry.

1127
00:59:46,748 --> 00:59:47,737
Oh.

1128
00:59:47,815 --> 00:59:51,217
Though my nasal passages
do become congested
when I'm sad.

1129
00:59:51,420 --> 00:59:54,115
Oh, don't be sad.
It's your birthday. Hmm?

1130
00:59:54,755 --> 00:59:56,849
Oh, I wish I could
celebrate with you tonight.

1131
00:59:56,925 --> 00:59:58,916
I just have to go out of town
for a few days.

1132
00:59:59,126 --> 01:00:00,115
Really?

1133
01:00:00,195 --> 01:00:03,130
Yes, I just have
some business to take care of.

1134
01:00:03,798 --> 01:00:05,824
But we'll celebrate
when I get back, all right?
Okay.

1135
01:00:07,869 --> 01:00:09,927
Thank you so much
for the present.
It's beautiful.

1136
01:00:10,005 --> 01:00:11,528
I'll think about you
whenever I wear it.

1137
01:00:11,606 --> 01:00:12,596
(CHUCKLES)

1138
01:00:14,675 --> 01:00:16,233
You didn't tell me
it was your birthday!

1139
01:00:16,311 --> 01:00:18,074
I'll take you
for a magnificent dinner.

1140
01:00:18,146 --> 01:00:19,943
We'll go
to a great restaurant.
Really?

1141
01:00:20,047 --> 01:00:24,007
(STUTTERING) Do you enjoy
the McNuggets thing?

1142
01:00:25,086 --> 01:00:28,318
What about Indian food?
Do you like spicy food?

1143
01:00:28,556 --> 01:00:30,320
No, no, it's okay.

1144
01:00:30,391 --> 01:00:32,326
I don't really have
much of an appetite.

1145
01:00:32,494 --> 01:00:35,257
But you will when
they bring out the prawns
in hydrochloric acid.

1146
01:00:35,329 --> 01:00:37,025
It's fantastic, Sondra.

1147
01:00:38,333 --> 01:00:40,233
What's the matter?

1148
01:00:40,302 --> 01:00:42,235
What,
are you thinking of Peter?
No.

1149
01:00:42,871 --> 01:00:44,168
I don't know, it's just...

1150
01:00:44,239 --> 01:00:46,706
I wouldn't be surprised
if he asked me to marry him
one day, you know?

1151
01:00:46,775 --> 01:00:49,402
You come
from an Orthodox family.

1152
01:00:49,478 --> 01:00:51,878
Would they accept
a serial killer?

1153
01:00:52,681 --> 01:00:54,342
That's an expensive present.

1154
01:00:55,483 --> 01:00:58,851
The Lymans are so wealthy.
Yes.

1155
01:00:58,920 --> 01:01:00,682
It was almost
too extravagant.

1156
01:01:01,088 --> 01:01:04,251
I'd better get ready.
I still haven't found
my millionaire yet.

1157
01:01:05,527 --> 01:01:06,516
(SIGHS)

1158
01:01:07,628 --> 01:01:10,097
Oh, God, Sondra, what a mess!

1159
01:01:12,300 --> 01:01:13,630
It's starting to add up
against him.

1160
01:01:13,702 --> 01:01:15,465
Bits and scraps
are coming together.

1161
01:01:15,536 --> 01:01:16,936
God, it's you!

1162
01:01:17,139 --> 01:01:19,733
I sensed
you were falling in love.
I escaped again.

1163
01:01:19,840 --> 01:01:23,469
It's just circumstantial junk,
you know. A coincidence
here and there.

1164
01:01:23,545 --> 01:01:25,570
Too much smoke
not to be fire.

1165
01:01:25,681 --> 01:01:28,012
Look, I'm sure
you've been wrong
plenty of times.

1166
01:01:28,083 --> 01:01:29,242
Not wrong here.

1167
01:01:29,317 --> 01:01:32,775
Though I agree
you haven't got enough
to pull the trigger yet.

1168
01:01:32,954 --> 01:01:35,184
If you act prematurely,
not only does he walk,

1169
01:01:35,257 --> 01:01:38,351
your professional credibility
is wrecked,
sometimes for good.

1170
01:01:38,427 --> 01:01:40,360
Oh, I'm sure you want him
to be guilty.

1171
01:01:40,461 --> 01:01:42,487
You know, that way you get
your last big scoop.

1172
01:01:42,597 --> 01:01:43,996
I'm beginning to fade.

1173
01:01:44,065 --> 01:01:45,896
Sondra, don't let me down!

1174
01:01:45,967 --> 01:01:48,059
I wish you'd fade for good!

1175
01:01:48,235 --> 01:01:49,396
Get out of my life!

1176
01:01:49,471 --> 01:01:50,903
I'm not
cut out for this.

1177
01:01:50,972 --> 01:01:53,496
I should be
flossing molars for a living.

1178
01:01:54,543 --> 01:01:57,239
The bread is... You know,
I can make a meal
just with the bread.

1179
01:01:57,311 --> 01:01:59,211
I can do a whole meal,
just nothing but bread.

1180
01:01:59,414 --> 01:02:02,246
If I ate that much bread,
I'd be 20 pounds heavier.

1181
01:02:02,317 --> 01:02:04,181
See,
I never gain an ounce,

1182
01:02:04,251 --> 01:02:08,382
because, you know,
my anxiety acts like aerobics.

1183
01:02:08,657 --> 01:02:10,056
So I get the exercise.

1184
01:02:10,891 --> 01:02:13,588
Thanks for taking me out
for my birthday, Sidney.

1185
01:02:13,695 --> 01:02:16,186
Well, you know,
you're the daughter
that I never had.

1186
01:02:16,264 --> 01:02:18,255
Oh, that's so...
No, no, I'm kidding.
I'm kidding.

1187
01:02:18,333 --> 01:02:19,731
'Cause I never wanted
to have kids.

1188
01:02:20,135 --> 01:02:22,432
I didn't.
Because you have kids,
what is it?

1189
01:02:22,737 --> 01:02:25,536
You know, you're nice
to them, you bring
them up, you suffer,

1190
01:02:25,606 --> 01:02:27,097
you take care of them

1191
01:02:27,175 --> 01:02:31,612
and then they grow up
and they accuse you
of having Alzheimer's.

1192
01:02:32,146 --> 01:02:33,739
Could you
ever live in London?

1193
01:02:35,317 --> 01:02:36,784
Could I live
in London? No.

1194
01:02:36,851 --> 01:02:39,047
And I love London.
Don't get me wrong,
I love London,

1195
01:02:39,121 --> 01:02:41,315
but, you know,

1196
01:02:41,623 --> 01:02:45,353
apart from
the language problem,
I can't take the driving.

1197
01:02:45,427 --> 01:02:48,487
Because it, you know,
it's on the wrong side,
and I...

1198
01:02:48,929 --> 01:02:50,726
Every time
I drive a car here,

1199
01:02:50,798 --> 01:02:53,063
I'm convinced
I'm going to die in a crash.

1200
01:02:54,402 --> 01:02:55,391
Sidney!

1201
01:02:55,570 --> 01:02:56,559
What's the matter?

1202
01:02:57,204 --> 01:02:58,501
It's Peter.

1203
01:02:58,572 --> 01:02:59,630
You said
Peter was out of town.

1204
01:02:59,708 --> 01:03:01,539
Well, that's
what he told me.

1205
01:03:02,110 --> 01:03:03,099
Come on.

1206
01:03:03,277 --> 01:03:04,539
What do you mean, come on?

1207
01:03:04,612 --> 01:03:06,773
(STUTTERING)
I ordered prawns.

1208
01:03:06,981 --> 01:03:09,074
Just pay, all right?
Just pay.

1209
01:03:09,351 --> 01:03:11,443
What do you mean, pay?
All I do is...

1210
01:03:11,519 --> 01:03:13,612
Fine, it's her birthday.

1211
01:03:16,891 --> 01:03:17,949
Come on.

1212
01:03:18,360 --> 01:03:20,487
Maybe he's got
another woman on the side,

1213
01:03:20,594 --> 01:03:23,563
and he likes you,
but he's sexually
attracted to her.

1214
01:03:23,864 --> 01:03:25,025
Thanks, Sidney.

1215
01:03:25,099 --> 01:03:26,726
Well, why doesn't he have
his chauffeur?

1216
01:03:26,802 --> 01:03:28,769
I don't know,
whatever he's doing,
he must want it to be secret.

1217
01:04:05,739 --> 01:04:08,072
Oh, I told you
he went the other way!

1218
01:04:08,543 --> 01:04:10,135
Can we go home, please?

1219
01:04:10,211 --> 01:04:11,974
It's starting to rain.

1220
01:04:12,047 --> 01:04:14,447
(GROANS) I can't believe
he lied to me.

1221
01:04:14,682 --> 01:04:18,346
Maybe he's doing
something that he's ashamed
to tell you about.

1222
01:04:18,420 --> 01:04:22,288
Maybe he belongs to
one of those clubs, or he's
a cross-dresser or something.

1223
01:04:22,356 --> 01:04:24,518
Or maybe
he does folk dancing.

1224
01:04:24,626 --> 01:04:27,059
Oh, I'm sure
it's probably something
that when he tells me,

1225
01:04:27,128 --> 01:04:29,152
I'll just feel foolish
for thinking he lied.

1226
01:04:29,231 --> 01:04:32,461
I'm sure. You know,
not everything in
this world is sinister.

1227
01:04:32,534 --> 01:04:34,297
You know,
just practically everything.

1228
01:04:34,369 --> 01:04:37,202
(GROANS) That Indian food
made me sick.

1229
01:04:37,771 --> 01:04:40,764
You hardly touched
your cobra salad.
How can you be sick?

1230
01:04:41,041 --> 01:04:42,804
WOMAN: (SCREAMING) Help!

1231
01:04:42,878 --> 01:04:45,539
A woman's been strangled!

1232
01:04:46,047 --> 01:04:50,449
Help!
A woman's been strangled!
Help, call the police!

1233
01:04:50,518 --> 01:04:52,509
MAN: Somebody call the police!
There's been a murder!

1234
01:04:52,586 --> 01:04:53,884
WOMAN 2: There's been
a murder upstairs.

1235
01:04:53,954 --> 01:04:54,943
WOMAN 1: Help!

1236
01:04:55,056 --> 01:04:57,047
MAN: Have you got a phone?
Have you got a phone?
Call the police.

1237
01:04:57,125 --> 01:04:59,922
Could it be the Tarot Killer?
They found a Tarot card.
It's him.

1238
01:04:59,994 --> 01:05:01,393
I can't believe it!
She lives in this building.

1239
01:05:01,463 --> 01:05:03,623
It's him again.
They found the Tarot card.

1240
01:05:05,266 --> 01:05:08,099
Elizabeth Gibson,
another short-haired brunette.

1241
01:05:08,335 --> 01:05:10,896
(SIGHS) We should have
gone to the police earlier.

1242
01:05:11,005 --> 01:05:14,032
Well, you know...
You said that they
wouldn't believe us

1243
01:05:14,108 --> 01:05:16,304
and they may not.

1244
01:05:16,677 --> 01:05:20,135
Sidney, it's about time
we show my story to
a real newspaperman.

1245
01:05:21,282 --> 01:05:22,614
By real, you mean what?

1246
01:05:22,784 --> 01:05:23,876
One that's living.

1247
01:05:24,318 --> 01:05:27,083
Vivian's father has a friend
that works at The Observer

1248
01:05:28,757 --> 01:05:31,054
Well, it's very vivid
and rather shocking,

1249
01:05:31,126 --> 01:05:33,958
and there are some
genuine circumstantial
bits of evidence.

1250
01:05:34,028 --> 01:05:37,760
But let me give you a lesson
in professional journalism.

1251
01:05:38,967 --> 01:05:42,561
No newspaper should
or would ever run this story.

1252
01:05:43,304 --> 01:05:44,795
What? Why?

1253
01:05:45,440 --> 01:05:48,568
It would be
fatally irresponsible
and libelous.

1254
01:05:49,244 --> 01:05:52,179
All you have here
are a number
of titillating speculations.

1255
01:05:53,047 --> 01:05:56,744
Flamboyant theories that
tarnish a man, and a
well-known figure at that,

1256
01:05:56,818 --> 01:05:59,378
without a single shred
of substantial proof.

1257
01:06:00,521 --> 01:06:02,682
So his mother
was a short-haired brunette.

1258
01:06:02,824 --> 01:06:04,655
So he came late
for a poker game

1259
01:06:04,726 --> 01:06:08,286
and said he was going away
on a business trip
and he got caught lying.

1260
01:06:08,596 --> 01:06:13,362
Yes, but who keeps
a Tarot deck under
a French horn?

1261
01:06:14,168 --> 01:06:18,195
It's not against the law
to own a Tarot deck,
or keep it wherever you like.

1262
01:06:19,641 --> 01:06:21,938
You'd look
pretty foolish in court
with your accusations,

1263
01:06:22,010 --> 01:06:23,637
and that's
where you'll wind up.

1264
01:06:24,012 --> 01:06:27,003
Because he'd have no choice
but to sue you
and the newspaper,

1265
01:06:27,081 --> 01:06:28,208
and he'd win.

1266
01:06:28,650 --> 01:06:30,014
And to go to the police?

1267
01:06:30,851 --> 01:06:32,045
I'll come to that.

1268
01:06:32,119 --> 01:06:35,282
But first let me
continue my tedious
professorial lecture.

1269
01:06:37,057 --> 01:06:39,184
Vivian's dad and I
go way back.

1270
01:06:39,594 --> 01:06:41,686
He said you were
a journalism student.

1271
01:06:42,463 --> 01:06:43,452
Hmm.

1272
01:06:44,498 --> 01:06:46,090
You talk about getting a tip.

1273
01:06:46,300 --> 01:06:48,132
Okay, you won't
disclose your source,

1274
01:06:48,202 --> 01:06:51,331
but what you have done
is let your imagination
run wild.

1275
01:06:51,472 --> 01:06:52,530
No, no.

1276
01:06:52,606 --> 01:06:56,168
What if I told you
that my source happened
to be a certain Joe Strombel?

1277
01:06:56,811 --> 01:06:58,710
The late Joe Strombel?
Yep.

1278
01:06:58,780 --> 01:07:01,213
You mean, before he died
he gave a student reporter

1279
01:07:01,282 --> 01:07:03,614
a major story
and didn't follow
it up himself?

1280
01:07:03,684 --> 01:07:06,380
We didn't say
it was before he died.

1281
01:07:07,521 --> 01:07:08,887
What?
No, it...

1282
01:07:08,956 --> 01:07:10,514
He got the story
before he died,

1283
01:07:10,592 --> 01:07:13,025
and then he died
before he could follow it up.

1284
01:07:14,762 --> 01:07:18,027
(CHUCKLES) Well,
why did he give it to you?
He didn't know he was dying.

1285
01:07:18,333 --> 01:07:19,492
I don't buy it.

1286
01:07:19,567 --> 01:07:21,125
I knew Joe Strombel well.

1287
01:07:21,469 --> 01:07:23,800
If he'd had a tip
that he considered reliable,

1288
01:07:24,438 --> 01:07:26,463
he would certainly
have pursued it himself,

1289
01:07:26,541 --> 01:07:28,440
from the grave,
if necessary.

1290
01:07:29,643 --> 01:07:32,442
What about how Peter
was in the neighborhood

1291
01:07:32,514 --> 01:07:34,539
the night
the murder was committed?

1292
01:07:34,648 --> 01:07:35,637
(CLEARS THROAT)

1293
01:07:35,750 --> 01:07:38,115
I realize as a student
how exciting it must have been

1294
01:07:38,186 --> 01:07:40,813
to think that you were onto
something so spectacular.

1295
01:07:40,954 --> 01:07:42,422
Hey, she is onto something!

1296
01:07:42,489 --> 01:07:44,548
This kid is a bloodhound.
Look at her!

1297
01:07:44,626 --> 01:07:48,152
She could sell the story
to any tabloid in town.

1298
01:07:48,797 --> 01:07:49,786
Hmm.

1299
01:07:50,731 --> 01:07:53,860
Now that I've preached
on the realities
of accurate reporting,

1300
01:07:53,934 --> 01:07:57,961
I want to tell you
how catastrophic
for everybody involved

1301
01:07:58,039 --> 01:08:00,166
it would have been
if you had, say, taken

1302
01:08:00,240 --> 01:08:03,369
the results
of your investigation
to a tabloid.

1303
01:08:04,711 --> 01:08:08,273
Today, the police
have apprehended
the Tarot Card Serial Killer.

1304
01:08:08,882 --> 01:08:11,646
And it most assuredly
is not Peter Lyman.

1305
01:08:12,152 --> 01:08:13,380
What?

1306
01:08:13,454 --> 01:08:16,548
Every paper in town
is going to press
with it as we speak.

1307
01:08:17,425 --> 01:08:21,155
It was a handyman
named Henry Banks
who has confessed.

1308
01:08:21,863 --> 01:08:25,025
Banks is a delusional paranoid
who's given Scotland Yard

1309
01:08:25,100 --> 01:08:27,761
information
that only the killer
could possibly know.

1310
01:08:28,603 --> 01:08:30,399
He's led the police
to two additional bodies

1311
01:08:30,471 --> 01:08:34,305
and his DNA
and a fingerprint
they found check out.

1312
01:08:35,409 --> 01:08:37,640
I know
this puts a crimp
in your scoop,

1313
01:08:38,479 --> 01:08:41,243
but Henry Banks is
the Tarot Card Serial Killer.

1314
01:08:42,149 --> 01:08:43,640
Not Lord Lyman's son.

1315
01:08:46,354 --> 01:08:48,150
Well, I can't say
I'm not walking on air.

1316
01:08:49,056 --> 01:08:52,253
Oh, Jesus, If I ever catch
that Joe Strombel,
I'll kill him.

1317
01:08:52,327 --> 01:08:54,318
I only hope
Peter forgives me
for what I've done.

1318
01:08:54,395 --> 01:08:55,487
For what?

1319
01:08:55,563 --> 01:08:57,497
I lied to him.
I'm not Jade Spence.

1320
01:08:57,564 --> 01:09:01,001
I'm a pushy,
duplicitous, ambitious
college student.

1321
01:09:01,069 --> 01:09:02,057
I lied to him,
over and over.

1322
01:09:02,170 --> 01:09:04,502
Darling, he lied to you, too,
so it's even.

1323
01:09:04,572 --> 01:09:07,972
His lies pale in comparison
to the enormity
of what I've done.

1324
01:09:08,475 --> 01:09:11,536
So marry him
as Jade Spence.
Don't tell him.

1325
01:09:11,613 --> 01:09:14,945
(STUTTERING) You know,
you don't have to be
Sondra Pransky ever again.

1326
01:09:15,015 --> 01:09:16,448
Marry him as Jade Spence.

1327
01:09:16,518 --> 01:09:19,543
Yeah, but I don't want to
have to get you a
Father's Day gift every year.

1328
01:09:19,887 --> 01:09:24,518
You know, I don't know how to
break this to you, honey,
but you were adopted. Okay?

1329
01:09:24,591 --> 01:09:26,525
Your mother and I,
we were at the orphanage,

1330
01:09:26,594 --> 01:09:28,891
we wanted
a handicapped child, and...

1331
01:09:29,631 --> 01:09:32,292
Ah, finally.
Just you and I all weekend.

1332
01:09:32,432 --> 01:09:33,421
Yeah.

1333
01:09:35,336 --> 01:09:36,894
I thought you'd like it here.

1334
01:09:37,104 --> 01:09:38,435
It's lovely.
Mmm-hmm.

1335
01:09:41,042 --> 01:09:42,703
Peter?
Yes.

1336
01:09:42,777 --> 01:09:45,301
I have
a confession to make.
Oh, God, so do I.

1337
01:09:45,813 --> 01:09:47,804
Oh, well, let me go first.

1338
01:09:47,881 --> 01:09:49,782
Actually, no,
let me, please,

1339
01:09:49,850 --> 01:09:51,148
because mine's
been bothering me all day.

1340
01:09:51,252 --> 01:09:52,582
I just want
to get it off my chest.

1341
01:09:52,654 --> 01:09:56,420
When I told you I was
going away for a few days
on business,

1342
01:09:56,557 --> 01:09:58,890
I was lying.

1343
01:09:59,726 --> 01:10:01,717
I know.
You know? How?

1344
01:10:02,396 --> 01:10:04,456
Oh, I saw you.
You saw me? No.

1345
01:10:04,798 --> 01:10:07,198
I was at dinner, and...
With your father?

1346
01:10:07,635 --> 01:10:10,832
Actually...
Well, anyway,
it doesn't matter. Really.

1347
01:10:11,206 --> 01:10:15,108
The truth is,
that a company my father owns

1348
01:10:15,176 --> 01:10:16,837
is about to merge
with a company
in the Middle East.

1349
01:10:16,911 --> 01:10:18,878
It's a very
sensitive situation,

1350
01:10:18,947 --> 01:10:20,641
and the less
anyone knows about it,
the better.

1351
01:10:20,715 --> 01:10:22,306
And we just didn't want
the press to sniff it out.

1352
01:10:22,382 --> 01:10:23,577
I mean,
that's no excuse, really.

1353
01:10:23,650 --> 01:10:25,983
I'm just very sorry
for the extreme secrecy.

1354
01:10:26,054 --> 01:10:29,113
No, no, no, it's fine.
I'm glad.

1355
01:10:29,189 --> 01:10:32,921
It's your own
secret information.
That's fine.

1356
01:10:32,993 --> 01:10:35,257
So your father took you out
for a birthday dinner

1357
01:10:35,329 --> 01:10:37,024
and you saw me.
I mean, how unnerving.

1358
01:10:37,097 --> 01:10:39,930
God, I mean, the thing
I hate most in the world
is lying.

1359
01:10:41,069 --> 01:10:42,194
Uh-huh.

1360
01:10:42,837 --> 01:10:43,895
What?

1361
01:10:45,606 --> 01:10:46,971
Peter...
Yes, Jade?

1362
01:10:48,542 --> 01:10:49,532
Peter...

1363
01:10:49,610 --> 01:10:51,703
Oh, yes.
What did you want to tell me?

1364
01:10:51,845 --> 01:10:52,869
Uh...

1365
01:10:52,947 --> 01:10:54,710
Jade, there's nothing
you can tell me that...

1366
01:10:54,782 --> 01:10:57,079
My name is not Jade Spence.

1367
01:10:58,118 --> 01:10:59,449
It's not?

1368
01:11:00,387 --> 01:11:02,480
No. It's Sondra Pransky.

1369
01:11:03,091 --> 01:11:06,720
And my father
is not my father.
His name is Sidney Waterman.

1370
01:11:06,793 --> 01:11:08,694
He's a magician
called Splendini.

1371
01:11:08,762 --> 01:11:10,287
I'm a journalism student.

1372
01:11:10,864 --> 01:11:15,063
Don't ask me
what kind of crazy
misinformation we received

1373
01:11:15,136 --> 01:11:17,069
to believe you might be
the Tarot Card Killer.

1374
01:11:17,137 --> 01:11:21,301
(STUTTERING) I mean,
I didn't know you
at this time. Remember?

1375
01:11:21,775 --> 01:11:24,609
And, of course,
as soon as I got to know you,

1376
01:11:24,679 --> 01:11:27,011
I knew that
it couldn't possibly be true.

1377
01:11:27,081 --> 01:11:29,207
And the police have him now,
so everything's fine.

1378
01:11:29,716 --> 01:11:32,117
Of course,
along the route
I fell for you,

1379
01:11:32,185 --> 01:11:34,814
and now
I totally blew it, and...

1380
01:11:34,889 --> 01:11:36,287
Who told you this?

1381
01:11:36,858 --> 01:11:39,952
Oh, a newspaperman.
He's now deceased.

1382
