01:24:12,813 --> 01:24:17,181
Mr. Lyman, sir, Mr. Spence
has been here and he's
been into the music room.

1606
01:24:17,951 --> 01:24:19,247
What do you mean?

1607
01:24:19,520 --> 01:24:21,511
A most unusual
sequence of events.

1608
01:24:21,587 --> 01:24:23,851
Mr. Spence came by
looking for his
daughter's sweater.

1609
01:24:23,923 --> 01:24:25,413
Said she'd requested it.

1610
01:24:25,492 --> 01:24:27,721
Next thing I knew,
he was in the music room.

1611
01:24:28,228 --> 01:24:30,719
Sir, I think
he'd been drinking,
from his behavior.

1612
01:24:31,664 --> 01:24:33,962
Yes, yes.

1613
01:24:34,568 --> 01:24:37,162
Yes. Okay, Margaret,
thank you. Goodbye.

1614
01:24:38,305 --> 01:24:39,465
Is everything okay?

1615
01:24:39,539 --> 01:24:42,407
Yes.
Yes, it will be.

1616
01:25:57,583 --> 01:26:00,576
It's so nice
to be out here with you,
just away

1617
01:26:01,587 --> 01:26:04,021
from the rest of the world
and...
Hmm.

1618
01:26:04,091 --> 01:26:08,585
Yes, I often
come out here to read and,
well, and fish.

1619
01:26:08,662 --> 01:26:10,152
There's trout in the lake.

1620
01:26:19,072 --> 01:26:20,595
What are you thinking about?

1621
01:26:21,774 --> 01:26:23,367
You really want to know?
Yes.

1622
01:26:25,878 --> 01:26:28,541
Just how ironic life is,
and tragic.

1623
01:26:29,082 --> 01:26:30,344
Why?

1624
01:26:30,917 --> 01:26:33,511
Well, that I met you
by rescuing you from drowning

1625
01:26:34,320 --> 01:26:36,152
and found you
totally enchanting

1626
01:26:37,291 --> 01:26:40,748
and now we've come full cycle
and, alas, you're going
to have to drown.

1627
01:26:43,796 --> 01:26:44,889
What?

1628
01:26:45,332 --> 01:26:48,426
Oh, I imagine by now
Sidney's confirmed
that I killed Betty Gibson.

1629
01:26:48,502 --> 01:26:51,095
I mean, in my own defense,
there really was
no other way out.

1630
01:26:52,139 --> 01:26:54,436
At first I managed
to hide my identity from her,

1631
01:26:54,507 --> 01:26:56,668
but I saw her too many times
over the years

1632
01:26:57,944 --> 01:26:59,707
and she learned who I was,
and...

1633
01:27:00,247 --> 01:27:02,408
Well, it became
a constant demand for money

1634
01:27:02,481 --> 01:27:04,712
and I just
could not let that go on,
could I?

1635
01:27:05,752 --> 01:27:07,743
I mean, my whole life
and career

1636
01:27:07,820 --> 01:27:10,654
would be
just hostage to her
moods at all times.

1637
01:27:12,893 --> 01:27:15,122
So, I studied
the Tarot case,

1638
01:27:15,194 --> 01:27:17,527
I rehearsed my plan,
and, well, you know the rest.

1639
01:27:17,631 --> 01:27:19,530
If you do something to me,
Sidney's gonna find out!

1640
01:27:19,600 --> 01:27:20,725
He'll tell someone.

1641
01:27:20,801 --> 01:27:23,360
No, no, no.
You see, you will go
in a boating accident,

1642
01:27:23,436 --> 01:27:25,131
and Sidney will go
later tonight.

1643
01:27:25,572 --> 01:27:27,733
No one knows
of your relationship with him,

1644
01:27:28,175 --> 01:27:30,699
because, after all,
you're not actually father
and daughter, are you?

1645
01:27:31,444 --> 01:27:34,505
And no one will think twice
to investigate the death
of some obscure vaud...

1646
01:27:34,581 --> 01:27:35,809
Are you listening?

1647
01:27:36,115 --> 01:27:37,980
No one will think twice
to investigate the death

1648
01:27:38,051 --> 01:27:41,612
of some obscure vaudevillian
called Splendini, who is
really a stranger to me.

1649
01:27:42,355 --> 01:27:43,380
Help!

1650
01:27:43,457 --> 01:27:45,220
Help! Someone help me!

1651
01:27:52,164 --> 01:27:53,826
(CHUCKLES)

1652
01:27:54,167 --> 01:27:55,759
Yes, very quiet, isn't it?

1653
01:27:59,072 --> 01:28:01,096
This is the advantage
of a private lake.

1654
01:28:05,212 --> 01:28:07,180
Get off me!
Get off me!

1655
01:28:07,247 --> 01:28:08,235
(GRUNTS)

1656
01:28:09,082 --> 01:28:10,242
Get off me!
Come...

1657
01:28:39,512 --> 01:28:41,140
(TIRES SCREECHING)

1658
01:28:41,213 --> 01:28:42,203
(CRASHING)

1659
01:28:42,282 --> 01:28:43,408
(GLASS SHATTERING)

1660
01:28:50,056 --> 01:28:51,649
(PANTING)

1661
01:29:29,595 --> 01:29:31,222
(FEIGNING CRYING)
Yes, police.

1662
01:29:32,899 --> 01:29:36,300
Yes, this is Peter Lyman.
I need the police immediately.

1663
01:29:36,869 --> 01:29:38,860
At the Lyman estate.

1664
01:29:39,372 --> 01:29:42,967
There's been
a terrible boating accident.
A woman has drowned.

1665
01:29:43,042 --> 01:29:44,738
It's awful.
Please come right away.

1666
01:29:44,810 --> 01:29:46,301
Thank you. Thank you.

1667
01:29:49,682 --> 01:29:51,014
(SIGHS)

1668
01:29:53,220 --> 01:29:54,914
They think they know
where the body is.

1669
01:29:56,122 --> 01:29:57,590
I'm so sorry, sir.

1670
01:30:00,761 --> 01:30:02,489
When last I saw her,
she...

1671
01:30:06,233 --> 01:30:08,724
She just said she wanted
to go out there to
communicate with nature.

1672
01:30:10,270 --> 01:30:12,203
Just to think
she wanted some
peace and quiet and...

1673
01:30:12,639 --> 01:30:14,663
She wasn't depressed,
or anything like that,
was she, sir?

1674
01:30:14,740 --> 01:30:15,729
God, no. No.

1675
01:30:16,076 --> 01:30:18,270
I mean, unless she was
keeping it from me.

1676
01:30:18,545 --> 01:30:20,206
You heard no cries for help?

1677
01:30:20,279 --> 01:30:23,738
No! No,
I was listening to music
in here, damn it.

1678
01:30:24,451 --> 01:30:26,042
(SIGHS) It's just so ironic.

1679
01:30:26,118 --> 01:30:27,244
Because the way
I first met her

1680
01:30:27,319 --> 01:30:29,550
I rescued her
from drowning
in our club pool.

1681
01:30:29,622 --> 01:30:32,113
And she was a very,
very weak swimmer.

1682
01:30:32,859 --> 01:30:34,019
SONDRA: Hello?

1683
01:30:35,295 --> 01:30:37,786
I was faking it at the pool
to get your attention.

1684
01:30:38,164 --> 01:30:41,225
Actually, I used to be
captain of the Brooklyn
Community Swim Team.

1685
01:30:56,115 --> 01:30:57,673
Fascinating observation.

1686
01:30:57,850 --> 01:31:00,444
Lyman lost a cufflink
at the flat of a prostitute,

1687
01:31:00,520 --> 01:31:02,988
who was later killed
by the Tarot Card Killer.

1688
01:31:04,157 --> 01:31:07,684
Well, this upright chap
certainly enjoyed patronizing
some dodgy women.

1689
01:31:08,161 --> 01:31:11,721
Unfortunately
for Elizabeth Gibson,
she elected to blackmail him.

1690
01:31:13,099 --> 01:31:15,123
It's a beautifully
written story

1691
01:31:15,268 --> 01:31:19,136
and one of the best bits
of investigative journalism
in a long time.

1692
01:31:19,506 --> 01:31:21,474
And this paper
is proud to run it.

1693
01:31:21,541 --> 01:31:23,940
Oh, I have to
share the credit
with Joe Strombel.

1694
01:31:24,243 --> 01:31:25,268
An inspiration,

1695
01:31:25,345 --> 01:31:27,711
who taught me more
than I could ever
explain to anyone.

1696
01:31:27,780 --> 01:31:30,545
And to the late
Sidney Waterman.

1697
01:31:31,283 --> 01:31:32,409
Splendini.

1698
01:31:32,551 --> 01:31:35,282
A nice guy who helped out
with the investigation

1699
01:31:35,354 --> 01:31:37,983
and without whom
I never could have made it.

1700
01:31:39,391 --> 01:31:41,882
Sidney, wherever you are,

1701
01:31:43,029 --> 01:31:44,462
I'll never forget you.

1702
01:31:46,832 --> 01:31:47,697
WOMAN: How did you get here?

1703
01:31:48,100 --> 01:31:49,158
Me?

1704
01:31:49,269 --> 01:31:52,966
I couldn't get used to driving
on the goddamn wrong
side of the street!

1705
01:31:53,038 --> 01:31:55,029
(STUTTERING) You know,
I was driving up
to the country,

1706
01:31:55,108 --> 01:31:58,042
and in the United States,
I would have been a hero.
I would have saved her.

1707
01:31:58,110 --> 01:31:59,100
I would have...

1708
01:31:59,179 --> 01:32:01,703
But here, you know...
That's the one drawback
of living in London.

1709
01:32:01,780 --> 01:32:04,908
Granted, the theater's better,
there's many good
Indian restaurants.

1710
01:32:04,984 --> 01:32:06,179
Well, what did you do?

1711
01:32:06,286 --> 01:32:08,845
What do I do?
I'm Splendini. Magician.

1712
01:32:08,954 --> 01:32:09,944
(EXCLAIMS)

1713
01:32:10,055 --> 01:32:12,024
Would you like
to see something?
Oh, yes, please.

1714
01:32:12,091 --> 01:32:13,752
Do we have time
for a card trick?
Yes.

1715
01:32:13,827 --> 01:32:15,521
I believe we have eternity.

1716
01:32:15,595 --> 01:32:17,961
I'm going to show you
a little trick now.

1717
01:32:18,430 --> 01:32:21,194
I just want to say
from the bottom of my heart,
I mean this sincerely...

1718
01:32:21,868 --> 01:32:23,233
I say this
with all due respect.

1719
01:32:23,302 --> 01:32:25,965
You are a wonderful group and
a fantastic group of people.

1720
01:32:26,038 --> 01:32:28,701
I love you and I feel that
coming back from you.

1721
01:32:28,774 --> 01:32:33,109
And you may be deceased,
but you should not
be discouraged.

1722
01:32:33,179 --> 01:32:34,510
Because, you know...

1723
01:32:34,581 --> 01:32:37,140
Don't think of being dead
as a handicap.

1724
01:32:37,216 --> 01:32:39,344
You know,
when I was a child,
I stuttered.

1725
01:32:39,418 --> 01:32:41,819
But with stick-to-it-iveness
and perseverance,

1726
01:32:41,887 --> 01:32:43,855
you know, you can never tell
what could happen.

1727
01:32:43,923 --> 01:32:45,356
Now, I want you
to take a card, Alma.

1728
01:32:45,425 --> 01:32:46,686
Go ahead,
take any card you want.

1729
01:32:46,760 --> 01:32:48,454
Just pick it. Pick it.
Go ahead, sweetheart.

1730
01:32:48,528 --> 01:32:50,256
I love you, sweetheart
That's fantastic
